[0.004, "o", "\u001b[1m\u001b[36m### How Gravity Bends Time (General Relativity)\u001b[39m\u001b[22m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[37mCore idea:\u001b[39m\u001b[22m Mass and energy don't just pull objects — they warp the fabric of spacetime itself. Time is part of\r\nthat fabric, so it gets warped too.\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0m---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[37m1. Spacetime as geometry\u001b[39m\u001b[22m\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0mEinstein replaced Newton's \"force of gravity\" with a geometric picture: massive objects curve the 4D spacetime\r\naround them. The Einstein field equations describe this:\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[2m\u001b[3m    \u001b[0mGμν + Λgμν = (8πG/c⁴) Tμν\u001b[0m\u001b[23m\u001b[22m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0mThe left side is spacetime curvature; the right side is the matter-energy content causing it.\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[37m2. Gravitational time dilation\u001b[39m\u001b[22m\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0mA clock in a stronger gravitational field (closer to a massive body) ticks \u001b[3m\u001b[35mslower\u001b[39m\u001b[23m than one farther away. For a\r\nnon-rotating, spherical mass, the Schwarzschil"]
[0.000, "o", "d metric gives:\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[2m\u001b[3m    \u001b[0mΔt_far = Δt_near / √(1 − 2GM/rc²)\u001b[0m\u001b[23m\u001b[22m\r\n\r\n    * \u001b[0m**G** — gravitational constant\u001b[0m\r\n    * \u001b[0m**M** — mass of the object\u001b[0m\r\n    * \u001b[0m**r** — distance from center of mass\u001b[0m\r\n    * \u001b[0m**c** — speed of light\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0mAs \u001b[1m\u001b[37mr\u001b[39m\u001b[22m decreases (closer to mass), the denominator shrinks, so the far-away observer measures \u001b[3m\u001b[35mmore\u001b[39m\u001b[23m elapsed time —\r\nthe near clock runs slow.\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[37m3. Real-world evidence\u001b[39m\u001b[22m\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n    * \u001b[0m**GPS satellites** — Clocks in orbit tick ~45 μs/day faster than ground clocks. Without correction, GPS would drift ~10 km/day.\u001b[0m\r\n    * \u001b[0m**Pound-Rebka experiment (1959)** — Measured gravitational redshift of photons in a 22.5m tower, matching GR predictions to 1%.\u001b[0m\r\n    * \u001b[0m**Hafele-Keating (1971)** — Atomic clocks flown on jets showed measurable time differences vs. ground clocks.\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[37m4. Intuition\u001b[39m\u001b[22m\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0mThink of spacetime as a stret"]
[0.000, "o", "ched rubber sheet. A heavy ball (mass) creates a dip. Near the dip, the \"surface\"\r\nis more curved — paths through time are compressed. Everything, including light and clocks, must follow this\r\ncurved geometry, so time itself runs differently depending on where you are in the gravitational well.\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0m---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[37mKey takeaway:\u001b[39m\u001b[22m Gravity doesn't \"pull\" on time — gravity \u001b[3m\u001b[35mis\u001b[39m\u001b[23m curved spacetime, and time dilation is a direct\r\ngeometric consequence of that curvature.\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\r\n"]
